"1190–1260","1190–1220":"1190–1220","1190":"1190","1227":"1227","1255":"1255","1220":"1220","1274":"1274","1250":"1255","1260":"1260","1308":"1308","1280":"1280","1218":"1218","Dunbartonshire, Scotland":"Dunbartonshire, Schotland","Luss, Dunbarton, Scotland":"Luss, Dunbartonshire, Schotland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Dunbarton, Dunbartonshire, Scotland":"Dumbarton, Dunbartonshire, Schotland","Dumbarton, Strathclyde, Scotland, United Kingdom":"Dumbarton, Dunbartonshire, Schotland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Dunbartonshire, Scotland, United Kingdom":"Dunbartonshire, Schotland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1220–1280":"1220–1280","1227–Female":"1227–Deceased","1255–1308":"1255–1308","1274–Male":"1274–Deceased","1190–1260":"1190–1260","1190–1220":"1190–1220","1190":"1190","1227":"1227","1255":"1255","1220":"1220","1274":"1274","1250":"1255","1260":"1260","1308":"1308","1280":"1280","1218":"1218","Dunbartonshire, Scotland":"Dunbartonshire, Scotland","Luss, Dunbarton, Scotland":"Luss, Dunbartonshire, Scotland, United Kingdom","Dunbarton, Dunbartonshire, Scotland":"Dumbarton, Dunbartonshire, Scotland","Dumbarton, Strathclyde, Scotland, United Kingdom":"Dumbarton, Dunbartonshire, Scotland, United Kingdom","Dunbartonshire, Scotland, United Kingdom":"Dunbartonshire, Scotland, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Colquhoun","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Scottish Alastair.","Scottish: habitational name from the barony of Colquhoun in Dumbartonshire. The name appears to derive from Gaelic <i>còil</i>, <i>cùil</i> ‘nook, corner’, or <i>coill(e)</i> ‘wood’ + <i>cumhann</i> ‘narrow’. The usual Scottish pronunciation is <i>ka-hoon</i>. This is the name of a Scottish family descended from Umfridus de Kilpatrick, who acquired lands in the barony of Colquhoun during the reign of Alexander II (1214–49)."],"variants":[{"name":"Cohoon","meanings":["English (Cheshire) and Scottish: variant of   Colquhoun  . This surname is now rare in Britain."]},{"name":"Calhoun","meanings":["Scottish: variant of   Colquhoun  .","History: This prominent early American name was brought across the Atlantic Ocean by Scotch-Irish pioneers who entered Pennsylvania <i>c.</i> 1733. The American statesman John <i>c.</i> Calhoun (1782–1850), born in Abbeville District, SC, served in both houses of Congress, was secretary of war, and vice president of the US (1825–32)."]},{"name":"Kahoun","meanings":["Irish: variant of Scottish   Colquhoun  ."]},{"name":"Cahoon","meanings":["Irish (Down and Antrim): variant (reflecting the traditional pronunciation) of Scottish   Colquhoun  ."]},{"name":"Calhoon","meanings":["Irish: variant of Scottish   Colquhoun  ."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Robert Colquhoun was born in 1220, in Dumbarton, Dunbartonshire, Scotland, United Kingdom, his father, Lord Umfridus first Colquhoun Kilpatrick, was 30 and his mother, Isobell Kilpatrick, was 30. He had at least 2 sons 